{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3946eb99-c5e4-4118-b34b-0f9b119f94b4","content":"PID 12345 isn't on this machine, so I can't inspect it directly. Here's how to diagnose and configure:\n\n## Step 1 — Determine the runtime\n\nRun these on your target machine:\n\n```bash\n# Check for CoreCLR shared libraries\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -c libcoreclr\n```\n\n- **Output > 0** → **CoreCLR** (the process loaded `libcoreclr.so`)\n- **Output = 0** → likely **NativeAOT** (single self-contained binary, no CLR)\n\nYou can also confirm NativeAOT with:\n```bash\nreadelf -d /proc/12345/exe | grep -c libcoreclr\n# 0 = NativeAOT (no dependency on libcoreclr.so)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 2 — Configure crash dumps\n\n### If CoreCLR\n\nCoreCLR has built-in dump support via environment variables. Set these before starting the app:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1          # Enable dumps on crash\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4            # 4 = Full heap dump (1=Mini, 2=WithHeap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t  # %p=PID, %t=timestamp\nmkdir -p /var/dumps\n```\n\nThese use the CoreCLR's `createdump` tool automatically on unhandled exceptions / crashes.\n\n### If NativeAOT\n\nNativeAOT apps don't include `createdump` — they behave like native Linux binaries. Use the **kernel core dump** mechanism:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Remove core file size limit\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# 2. Configure kernel core pattern (requires root)\necho '/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# 3. Make persistent across reboots\necho 'kernel.core_pattern=/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.d/90-coredump.conf\nsudo sysctl -p /etc/sysctl.d/90-coredump.conf\n\nmkdir -p /var/dumps\n```\n\n> **Note:** If your system uses **systemd-coredump** (check with `coredumpctl`), dumps are already collected under `/var/lib/systemd/coredump/` and you can retrieve them with `coredumpctl dump 12345`.\n\n---\n\n## Quick reference\n\n| | CoreCLR | NativeAOT |\n|---|---|---|\n| Detection | `libcoreclr.so` in `/proc/PID/maps` | No CLR libraries loaded |\n| Dump mechanism | `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` | Kernel `core_pattern` / systemd-coredump |\n| Analysis tool | `dotnet-dump analyze` | `gdb` or `lldb` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c2990758-40be-4efb-aaff-3b108a386222","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine. That's expected — the user said they have an app running on Linux with PID 12345, but it's not on this machine. I should provide them with guidance on how to determine the runtime and configure dumps accordingly.","outputTokens":829},"id":"c0a88dc9-e754-4c2b-9fc0-9d2359986622","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:06:54.683Z","parentId":"6fcaeb31-93fc-4364-a329-8a4dd52d0daf"}
